89
00:06:59,370 --> 00:07:03,824
The kinetic energy of an alpha
particle from nuclear decay is

90
00:07:03,824 --> 00:07:06,982
typically of the order of 5 MeV.

91
00:07:06,982 --> 00:07:11,327
When such a low energy particle
approaches a heavy nucleus from outside,

92
00:07:11,327 --> 00:07:14,530
it cannot penetrate the Coulomb barrier.

93
00:07:14,530 --> 00:07:23,190
For a nucleus of mass number about 200,
it has a typical height of 20 to 25 MeV.

94
00:07:23,190 --> 00:07:26,745
So why does the process work
in the opposite direction?

95
00:07:26,745 --> 00:07:31,450
How can an alpha particle traverse
the Coulomb barrier from the inside?

96
00:07:32,510 --> 00:07:36,660
The answer is given by
the quantum process of tunneling.

97
00:07:36,660 --> 00:07:40,743
The probability that
an alpha particle traverses

98
00:07:40,743 --> 00:07:45,708
the Coulomb barrier is of
the order of 10^-40.

99
00:07:45,708 --> 00:07:50,071
But this is the probability of
traversing on a single trial.

100
00:07:50,071 --> 00:07:52,800
This is why a low energy alpha particle

101
00:07:52,800 --> 00:07:56,647
from the outside cannot
penetrate the barrier.

102
00:07:56,647 --> 00:08:01,920
The velocity of an alpha particle,
bound to a nucleus with kinetic

103
00:08:01,920 --> 00:08:08,030
